Expectation ( or mean) Variance

Median \(X\) (discrete random variables)

\[E(X)=\sum_x xP(X=x)\]

\(X\) \(\mu\)

Variance (dispersion/variability)

\[Var(X)=E((X-\mu)^2)\\\text{Where, }\mu=E(x)\]

\[Var(X)=E(X^2)-E(X)^2\]

\[ \begin{align} Var(x) &= E((X-\mu)^2) \\ &= E(X^2-2X\mu+\mu^2)\\ &= E(X^2) - 2\mu E(X) + \mu^2\\ &= E(X^2) - 2\mu^2 + \mu^2 \\ &= E(X^2) - \mu^2 \\ &= E(X^2) - E(X)^2 \end{align} \]

  1. \(Var(X+b)=Var(X)\)
  2. \(Var(aX)=a^2Var(X)\)
  3. \(Var(aX+b)=a^2Var(X)\)

Bernoulli distribution

(1, 0)1 \(\pi\):

\[ \begin{align} E(X) &=\sum_x xP(X=x) \\ &=1\times\pi + 0\times(1-\pi)\\ &=\pi \end{align} \]

\(x=x^2\) \(x=0,1\), \(E[X^2]=E[X]\)

\[ \begin{align} Var(X) &=E[X^2]-E[X]^2 \\ &=E[X]-E[X]^2 \\ &=\pi - \pi^2 \\ &=\pi(1-\pi) \end{align} \]

\(X,Y\)
a) \(E(XY)=E(X)E(Y)\) ;
b) \(Var(X+Y)=Var(X)+Var(Y)\)

\[ \begin{align} E(XY) &= \sum_x\sum_y xyP(X=x, Y=y) \\ \because &\; X,Y \text{are independent to each other} \\ \therefore &= \sum_x\sum_y xyP(X=x)P(Y=y)\\ &=\sum_x xP(X=x)\sum_y yP(Y=y)\\ &=E(X)E(Y) \end{align} \]

\[ \begin{align} Var(X+Y) &= E((X+Y)^2)-E(X+Y)^2 \\ & \; \text{Expand} \\ &=E(X^2+2XY+Y^2)-(E(X)+E(Y))^2\\ &=E(X^2)+E(Y^2)+2E(XY)\\ &\;\;\; - E(X)^2-E(Y)^2-2E(X)E(Y)\\ &\; \text{We just showed}\; E(XY)=E(X)E(Y)\\ &=E(X^2)-E(X)^2+E(Y^2)-E(Y)^2 \\ &=Var(X)+Var(Y) \end{align} \]

Binomial distribution

\(n\) \(\pi\) (\(n\) independent Bernoulli trials)

\(X\) \(X \sim binomial(n, \pi)\) \(X \sim bin(n, \pi)\)( \(x\) )

\[ \begin{align} P(X=x) &= ^nC_x\pi^x(1-\pi)^{n-x} \\ &= \binom{n}{x}\pi^x(1-\pi)^{n-x} \\ & for\;\; x = 0,1,2,\dots,n \end{align} \]

  • \(E(X)\)
    • \(X \sim bin(n,\pi)\) \(X\)
    • \(X_i, i =1,\dots, n\)
    • \(X=\sum_{i=1}^nX_i\)

\[ \begin{align} E(X) &= E(\sum_{i=1}^nX_i)\\ &= E(X_1+X_2+\cdots+X_n) \\ &= E(X_1)+E(X_2)+\cdots+E(X_n)\\ &= \sum_{i=1}^nE(X_i)\\ &= \sum_{i=1}^n\pi \\ &= n\pi \end{align} \]

  • \(Var(X)\)

\[ \begin{align} Var(X) &= Var(\sum_{i=1}^nX_i) \\ &= Var(X_i+X_2+\cdots+X_n) \\ &= Var(X_i)+Var(X_2)+\cdots+Var(X_n) \\ &= \sum_{i=1}^nVar(X_i) \\ &= n\pi(1-\pi) \\ \end{align} \]

Poisson Distribution

  • (\(T\)) \(\lambda\) \(T\) \(E(X)=\lambda T\)
  • \(T\) \(n\) \(n\rightarrow\infty\)

  • \(T\)

\(X=\)

  • \(X \sim Bin(n, \pi)\) \(n\rightarrow\infty\)\(n\)
  • \(\pi=\frac{\lambda T}{n}\)
  • \(\mu=\lambda T \Rightarrow \pi=\mu/n\)
  • \(X\)

\[ \begin{align} P(X=x) &= \binom{n}{x}\pi^x(1-\pi)^{n-x} \\ &= \binom{n}{x}(\frac{\mu}{n})^x(1-\frac{\mu}{n})^{n-x} \\ &= \frac{n!}{x!(n-x)!}(\frac{\mu}{n})^x(1-\frac{\mu}{n})^{n-x} \\ &=\frac{n!}{n^x(n-x)!}\frac{\mu^x}{x!}(1-\frac{\mu}{n})^{n-x}\\ \text{when}\; n\rightarrow\infty &\; x \ll n\\ \frac{n!}{n^x(n-x)!} &=\frac{n(n-1)\dots(n-x+1)}{n^x} \rightarrow 1\\ (1-\frac{\mu}{n})^{n-x} &\approx (1-\frac{\mu}{n})^n \rightarrow e^{-\mu}\\ \text{the probability function } & \text{ of a Poisson distribution} \\ P(X=x) &\rightarrow \frac{\mu^x}{x!}e^{-\mu} \end{align} \]

\(X\sim Poisson(\mu=\lambda T)\;\; or\;\; X\sim Poi(\mu)\)

  1. \(E(X)=\mu\)

\[ \begin{align} E(X) &= \sum_{x=0}^\infty xP(X=x) \\ &= \sum_{x=0}^\infty x\frac{\mu^x}{x!}e^{-\mu} \\ &= 0+ \sum_{x=1}^\infty x\frac{\mu^x}{x!}e^{-\mu} \\ &= \sum_{x=1}^\infty \frac{\mu^x}{(x-1)!}e^{-\mu} \\ &= \mu\sum_{x=1}^\infty \frac{\mu^{x-1}}{(x-1)!}e^{-\mu} \\ \text{replace}\; &x\; \text{with all}\; i=x-1 \\ &= \mu\sum_{i=0}^\infty \frac{\mu^{i}}{i!}e^{-\mu} \\ \text{notice that}\; & \text{the right side} \sum_{i=0}^\infty \frac{\mu^{i}}{i!}e^{-\mu}=1 is \\ \text{the sum of all}\;& \text{probability of a Poisson distribution}\\ &= \mu \end{align} \]

  1. \(Var(x)=\mu\) \(Var(X)\) \(Var(X)=E(X^2)-E(X)^2\)

\(E(X^2)\)

\[ \begin{align} E(X^2) &= \sum_{x=0}^\infty x^2\frac{\mu^x}{x!}e^{-\mu} \\ &= \mu \sum_{x=1}^\infty x\frac{\mu^{x-1}}{(x-1)!}e^{-\mu} \\ \text{replace}\; &x\; \text{with all}\; i=x-1 \\ &= \mu \sum_{i=0}^\infty (i+1)\frac{\mu^{i}}{i!}e^{-\mu} \\ &= \mu(\sum_{i=0}^\infty i\frac{\mu^i}{i!}e^{-\mu} + \sum_{i=0}^\infty \frac{\mu^i}{i!}e^{-\mu}) \\ &= \mu(E(X)+1) \\ &= \mu^2+\mu \\ Var(X) &= E(X^2) - E(X)^2 \\ &= \mu^2 + \mu -\mu^2 \\ &= \mu \end{align} \]

Covariance

\(X,Y\) Variance

\[\text{Var}(X+Y)=\text{Var}(X)+\text{Var}(Y)\]

\[ \begin{aligned} \text{Var}(X+Y) &= E[((X+Y)-E(X+Y))^2] \\ &= E[(X+Y)-(E(X)+E(Y))^2] \\ &= E[(X-E(X)) - (Y-E(Y))^2] \\ &= E[(X-E(X))^2+(Y-E(Y))^2 \\ & \;\;\; +2(X-E(X))(Y-E(Y))] \\ &= \text{Var}(X)+\text{Var}(Y)+2E[(X-E(X))(Y-E(Y))] \end{aligned} \]

\(E[(X-E(X))(Y-E(Y))]\) \((X, Y)\) (Covariance): \[\text{Cov}(X,Y) = E[(X-E(X))(Y-E(Y))]\]

\[\text{Var}(X+Y)=\text{Var}(X)+\text{Var}(Y)+2Cov(X,Y)\]

\(X,Y\) (Linear Association)

(Covariance)

  1. \(\text{Cov}(X,X)=\text{Var}(X)\)
  2. \(\text{Cov}(X,Y)=\text{Cov}(Y,X)\)
  3. \(\text{Cov}(aX,bY)=ab\:\text{Cov}(X,Y)\)
  4. \[\text{Cov}(aR+bS,cX+dY)=ac\:\text{Cov}(R,X)+ad\:\text{Cov}(R,Y)\\ \;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;+bc\:\text{Cov}(S,X)+bd\:\text{Cov}(S,Y)\]
  5. \[\text{Cov}(aX+bY,cX+dY)=ac\:\text{Var}(X)+ad\:\text{Var}(Y)\\ \;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;+(ad+bc)\text{Cov}(X,Y)\]
  6. \(\text{Cov}(X+Y,X-Y)=\text{Var}(X)-\text{Var}(Y)\)
  7. If \(X, Y\) are independent. \(\text{Cov}(X,Y)=0\) But not vise-versa !

Correlation

  • \(\text{Cov}(X,Y)\)
  • ( s.d.) (standardization) Corr (\(-1\sim1\)): \[\text{Corr}(X,Y)=\frac{\text{Cov}(X,Y)}{\text{SD}(X)\text{SD}(Y)}=\frac{\text{Cov}(X,Y)}{\sqrt{\text{Var}(X)\text{Var}(Y)}}\]

  1. \(6\) \(2\) (Find the distribution of leg length age 6 conditional on leg length at age 2.)

\(6\) \(2\) (correlation, \(\rho_{6,2}\))

\[ \begin{aligned} \rho_{6,2} &= \frac{Cov_{6,2}}{\sqrt{\text{Var}(\text{length}_6)}\sqrt{\text{Var}(\text{length}_2)}}\\ &= \frac{13.7}{\sqrt{22.2}\sqrt{29}}=0.54 \end{aligned} \]

\[ \begin{aligned} E({\text{length}_6 | \text{length}_2}) &= \mu_6+\frac{\rho_{6,2}\sigma_6}{\sigma_2}(\text{length}_2-\mu_2) \\ &= 114+\frac{0.54\times\sqrt{29.0}}{\sqrt{22.2}}(\text{length}_2-85)\\ \text{Var}(\text{length}_6 | \text{length}_2) &= \sigma_6^2(1-\rho_{6,2}^2) \\ &= 29.0\times(1-0.54^2) =20.5 \end{aligned} \]
